{"author":{"id":"138b13306404778af60b1d60d606624fec41556ddac480b2d5f762806ce84fed"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1783028619,"nonce":"CkjgbjNLRaZCBz1nSQO2VFVm1Bw=","kind":"spec","title":"kref show markdown reflow + global --plain — design spec (approved 2026-07-02)"},{"type":3,"timestamp":1783028619,"nonce":"4TgowxUGVHiU2J4KHPtvejRymn8=","body":"# `show` markdown reflow + global `--plain` — design spec\n\n**Status: approved by Trevor, 2026-07-02.** Companion decisions made in the same session; ship together as one arc.\n\n## Problem\n\nLLM-authored entries arrive hard-wrapped at ~78 columns. Rendered reading (`kref show`, pager) preserves that tight wrapping, which makes entries painful to read: the renderer wraps long lines down to terminal width but never joins short ones back up.\n\nEmpirical findings (glamour v1.0.0, verified 2026-07-02 against entry 81be409e4ef8):\n\n- Top-level paragraphs DO reflow when word wrap \u003e 0. With word wrap = 0 (the pipe path) source line breaks are preserved verbatim.\n- List-item continuation lines NEVER reflow — goldmark parses tight list content as `TextBlock` and glamour renders its soft breaks as newlines. LLM prose is bullet-heavy, so this is the dominant pain.\n- Blockquotes reflow but with orphan-word artifacts (a single word stranded on its own line).\n- glamour v2.0.1 (module path moved to `charm.land/glamour/v2`) fixes the blockquote orphans but still does not reflow list continuation lines. Upgrading alone does not fix the problem → upgrade rejected (new module path + style API churn for no gain; once input paragraphs are single lines, v1 wraps cleanly).\n\n## Decision 1 — render-time soft-break unwrapping\n\nUnwrap soft line breaks in markdown BEFORE glamour sees it. Display-time only: stored content is never mutated; `--json` and plain output stay byte-faithful.\n\nMechanism (`internal/render/unwrap.go`, unexported `unwrapMarkdown(src string) string`):\n\n1. Parse with goldmark + `extension.GFM` — matching glamour's block grammar. GFM matters: without the table extension a table parses as a paragraph and would be joined into soup.\n2. Walk the AST for `Paragraph` and `TextBlock` nodes (TextBlock is tight-list-item content — the exact construct glamour refuses to reflow). Each node's `Lines()` segments map one-to-one onto source lines; segment offsets exclude the structural prefix (`\u003e `, list indent).\n3. Rebuild the document line by line: the first line of each block keeps its original prefix (list marker, `\u003e `, indent); continuation lines drop their prefix and join onto the previous line with a single space. Every line not belonging to a Paragraph/TextBlock — fences, indented code, tables, headings, HTML, blanks, thematic breaks — is emitted verbatim.\n4. Hard breaks (trailing two-plus spaces or backslash) keep their newline. CRLF input handled without leaving stray `\\r`.\n\nWire-in: `RenderBody` calls `unwrapMarkdown(body)` once, before all three glamour paths, guarded by the existing `content.IsMarkdown`. Pager, gutter, TTY, and pipe all inherit the fix. Reflow applies at every width, including the width=0 pipe path (piped rendered output becomes one line per paragraph — decided deliberately: piped `show` output is already rendered, not raw; the byte-stable contracts are `--plain` and `--json`). The existing verbatim fallback in `RenderBody` still applies if glamour errors.\n\nDependency: goldmark v1.7.13 promoted from indirect to direct in go.mod — zero new bytes in the module graph; it is glamour's own parser.\n\nRejected alternatives:\n\n- Hand-rolled line state machine — must reimplement fences, nested list continuation, lazy blockquote continuation, and the 4-space \"indented code vs list continuation\" ambiguity; a bug silently corrupts rendered entries.\n- Ingest-time normalization — mutates authored content, violates fidelity, does not fix existing entries.\n- glamour v2 upgrade — see findings above.\n\n## Decision 2 — global `--plain`, `show --raw` removed\n\n`--plain` becomes a persistent root flag alongside `--json`, defined once: \"chrome-free, line-oriented output for grep/cut/xargs\". `--plain` and `--json` are mutually exclusive (`MarkFlagsMutuallyExclusive`) — erroring beats silently picking one.\n\nPer-command mapping:\n\n- `list` — exactly the current local `--plain` (TSV via `plainCell`, uncollapsed, no footer). Local flag definition removed; the `--new` interaction guard reads the global.\n- `search` — NEW: TSV rows (matches, tier, id, kind, title), no footer.\n- `show` — verbatim body, no header block. The `--raw` flag is REMOVED (breaking, CHANGELOG; pre-release so free). `render.ShowOptions.Raw` survives as the internal mechanism; the CLI maps `--plain` onto it. `--no-header` stays for \"rendered but headerless\".\n- everywhere else (`log`, `diff`, …) — harmless no-op, same convention as `NO_COLOR`.\n\n`--plain` implies no color and no pager — it is a machine contract and behaves like one even on a TTY. Because `--plain` on `show` bypasses `RenderBody`, it is automatically the escape hatch from reflow: rendered output reflows, `--plain`/`--json` are stable.\n\nNaming rationale: a global `--raw` was considered and rejected — `show --raw` promises byte fidelity, but list/search TSV cells are formatted projections (dates, joined labels). `--plain` is the one name that honestly covers both.\n\n## Testing\n\nGinkgo specs alongside the existing render suite:\n\n- wrapped paragraph joins; wrapped bullets (nested, task-list) join with markers preserved; blockquote joins to a single `\u003e ` line\n- fenced/indented code, tables, headings, HTML untouched; hard breaks and CRLF preserved\n- real-world regression case: a bullet with continuation lines renders reflowed at width 100\n- `show --plain` byte-fidelity, `search --plain` TSV shape, `--plain --json` mutual-exclusion error\n- e2e goldens pinning old piped output updated deliberately; `task check` green\n\n## Docs\n\nREADME + CHANGELOG: \"rendered markdown reflows soft-wrapped paragraphs; use `--plain` for the stored bytes\"; document the `--raw` removal and the global `--plain` contract."},{"type":9,"timestamp":1783028619,"nonce":"DVzHSVWm+4R0q524ew/dQPGfdRQ=","label":"area:design"},{"type":11,"timestamp":1783028619,"nonce":"K4HN6f1vKCdkEnEaLB5J6AQRpcs=","actor":"Trevor Vaughan","actor_kind":"human","source_path":"","trigger":"create"},{"type":4,"timestamp":1783028880,"nonce":"cYpuHxrdTcb44XI4CivgejHq3A8=","title":"`show` markdown reflow + global `--plain` — design spec"},{"type":2,"timestamp":1783028971,"nonce":"2oxXYt5jzxZzuKFbbrphcwxU+K4=","status":"accepted"},{"type":3,"timestamp":1783029229,"nonce":"zEXt9X19x1eox0teyzHO59sb/5M=","body":"# `show` markdown reflow + global `--plain` — design spec\n\n**Status: approved by Trevor, 2026-07-02.** Companion decisions made in the same session; ship together as one arc.\n\n## Problem\n\nLLM-authored entries arrive hard-wrapped at ~78 columns. Rendered reading (`kref show`, pager) preserves that tight wrapping, which makes entries painful to read: the renderer wraps long lines down to terminal width but never joins short ones back up.\n\nEmpirical findings (glamour v1.0.0, verified 2026-07-02 against entry 81be409e4ef8):\n\n- Top-level paragraphs DO reflow when word wrap \u003e 0. With word wrap = 0 (the pipe path) source line breaks are preserved verbatim.\n- List-item continuation lines NEVER reflow — goldmark parses tight list content as `TextBlock` and glamour renders its soft breaks as newlines. LLM prose is bullet-heavy, so this is the dominant pain.\n- Blockquotes reflow but with orphan-word artifacts (a single word stranded on its own line).\n- glamour v2.0.1 (module path moved to `charm.land/glamour/v2`) fixes the blockquote orphans but still does not reflow list continuation lines — upgrading alone does not fix the problem. Both changes are needed; see Decision 3.\n\n## Decision 1 — render-time soft-break unwrapping\n\nUnwrap soft line breaks in markdown BEFORE glamour sees it. Display-time only: stored content is never mutated; `--json` and plain output stay byte-faithful.\n\nMechanism (`internal/render/unwrap.go`, unexported `unwrapMarkdown(src string) string`):\n\n1. Parse with goldmark + `extension.GFM` — matching glamour's block grammar. GFM matters: without the table extension a table parses as a paragraph and would be joined into soup.\n2. Walk the AST for `Paragraph` and `TextBlock` nodes (TextBlock is tight-list-item content — the exact construct glamour refuses to reflow). Each node's `Lines()` segments map one-to-one onto source lines; segment offsets exclude the structural prefix (`\u003e `, list indent).\n3. Rebuild the document line by line: the first line of each block keeps its original prefix (list marker, `\u003e `, indent); continuation lines drop their prefix and join onto the previous line with a single space. Every line not belonging to a Paragraph/TextBlock — fences, indented code, tables, headings, HTML, blanks, thematic breaks — is emitted verbatim.\n4. Hard breaks (trailing two-plus spaces or backslash) keep their newline. CRLF input handled without leaving stray `\\r`.\n\nWire-in: `RenderBody` calls `unwrapMarkdown(body)` once, before all three glamour paths, guarded by the existing `content.IsMarkdown`. Pager, gutter, TTY, and pipe all inherit the fix. Reflow applies at every width, including the width=0 pipe path (piped rendered output becomes one line per paragraph — decided deliberately: piped `show` output is already rendered, not raw; the byte-stable contracts are `--plain` and `--json`). The existing verbatim fallback in `RenderBody` still applies if glamour errors.\n\nDependency: goldmark v1.7.13 promoted from indirect to direct in go.mod — zero new bytes in the module graph; it is glamour's own parser.\n\nRejected alternatives:\n\n- Hand-rolled line state machine — must reimplement fences, nested list continuation, lazy blockquote continuation, and the 4-space \"indented code vs list continuation\" ambiguity; a bug silently corrupts rendered entries.\n- Ingest-time normalization — mutates authored content, violates fidelity, does not fix existing entries.\n\n## Decision 2 — global `--plain`, `show --raw` removed\n\n`--plain` becomes a persistent root flag alongside `--json`, defined once: \"chrome-free, line-oriented output for grep/cut/xargs\". `--plain` and `--json` are mutually exclusive (`MarkFlagsMutuallyExclusive`) — erroring beats silently picking one.\n\nPer-command mapping:\n\n- `list` — exactly the current local `--plain` (TSV via `plainCell`, uncollapsed, no footer). Local flag definition removed; the `--new` interaction guard reads the global.\n- `search` — NEW: TSV rows (matches, tier, id, kind, title), no footer.\n- `show` — verbatim body, no header block. The `--raw` flag is REMOVED (breaking, CHANGELOG; pre-release so free). `render.ShowOptions.Raw` survives as the internal mechanism; the CLI maps `--plain` onto it. `--no-header` stays for \"rendered but headerless\".\n- everywhere else (`log`, `diff`, …) — harmless no-op, same convention as `NO_COLOR`.\n\n`--plain` implies no color and no pager — it is a machine contract and behaves like one even on a TTY. Because `--plain` on `show` bypasses `RenderBody`, it is automatically the escape hatch from reflow: rendered output reflows, `--plain`/`--json` are stable.\n\nNaming rationale: a global `--raw` was considered and rejected — `show --raw` promises byte fidelity, but list/search TSV cells are formatted projections (dates, joined labels). `--plain` is the one name that honestly covers both.\n\n## Decision 3 — upgrade glamour to v2 (charm.land/glamour/v2)\n\nOriginally rejected as \"no gain\", reversed on new evidence (approved by Trevor, 2026-07-02): even with single-line input, glamour v1 blockquote wrapping glitches — orphan words and wrapped lines that lose their `|` margin marker. v2.0.1 renders unwrapped input cleanly across every construct tested.\n\nPort cost, verified empirically against a scratch module before approval:\n\n- import path swap: `github.com/charmbracelet/glamour` → `charm.land/glamour/v2`, `.../glamour/ansi` → `charm.land/glamour/v2/ansi`.\n- `plainMarkdownStyle` (ansi.StyleConfig/StyleBlock/StylePrimitive) compiles and renders UNCHANGED against v2.\n- `WithStandardStyle`, `WithStyles`, `WithWordWrap`, `NewTermRenderer`, `Render` — all used APIs unchanged.\n- new transitive deps under charm.land / lipgloss v2; glamour v1 deps drop out.\n- the plain (piped) style shifts blank-line placement slightly → affected e2e goldens updated deliberately in this arc.\n\n## Testing\n\nGinkgo specs alongside the existing render suite:\n\n- wrapped paragraph joins; wrapped bullets (nested, task-list) join with markers preserved; blockquote joins to a single `\u003e ` line\n- fenced/indented code, tables, headings, HTML untouched; hard breaks and CRLF preserved\n- real-world regression case: a bullet with continuation lines renders reflowed at width 100\n- `show --plain` byte-fidelity, `search --plain` TSV shape, `--plain --json` mutual-exclusion error\n- e2e goldens pinning old piped output updated deliberately; `task check` green\n\n## Docs\n\nREADME + CHANGELOG: \"rendered markdown reflows soft-wrapped paragraphs; use `--plain` for the stored bytes\"; document the `--raw` removal and the global `--plain` contract.\n\n## Amendment log\n\n- 2026-07-02: Decision 3 added (glamour v2 upgrade), reversing the original rejection; blockquote glitch evidence from rendering entry 81be409e4ef8 unwrapped through both versions.\n"},{"type":11,"timestamp":1783133415,"nonce":"4zUHF7JF/vvCe+BIpxs+I7rWnz8=","actor":"Trevor Vaughan","actor_kind":"human","source_path":"","trigger":"retier"}]}